Got it 👍 — you want to **remove current GitHub connection and connect a new account**. I’ll give you **simple step-by-step**.

---
# 🔴 Step 1: Remove old Git config (name & email)

```bash
git config --global --unset user.name
git config --global --unset user.email
```
👉 Check:
```bash
git config --global --list
```
# 🔴 Step 2: Remove old SSH key (important)
```bash
ls ~/.ssh
👉 Remove old key:

```bash
rm ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
rm ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```
# 🔴 Step 3: Create new SSH key (new account)

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_new_email@gmail.com"
Press Enter → Enter → Enter
# 🔴 Step 4: Add key to SSH agent

```bash
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
```

---

# 🔴 Step 5: Copy key

```bash
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```

👉 Copy full output

---

# 🔴 Step 6: Add to GitHub

* Go to GitHub → Settings
* SSH and GPG keys
* Click **New SSH Key**
* Paste → Save

---

# 🔴 Step 7: Set new Git config

```bash
git config --global user.name "New Name"
git config --global user.email "your_new_email@gmail.com"
```

---

# 🔴 Step 8: Test connection

```bash
ssh -T git@github.com
```

👉 Should show:

```bash
Hi NEW_USERNAME! You've successfully authenticated...
```

---

# 🧠 Important Note

If you already cloned repos:

```bash
git remote -v
```

👉 If needed, update:

```bash
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:NEW_USERNAME/repo.git
```

